You are working on HYDRA, an AI-powered SOC automation platform.

Read CLAUDE.md at repo root for full project context.

Key rules:
- Go API in api/ — uses Gin framework, package main
- Python worker in worker/ — uses Temporal SDK, psycopg2 for DB
- All database queries must be tenant-scoped (WHERE tenant_id = $X)
- All new migrations go in migrations/ with next sequential number (after 040)
- Tests: Go in api/*_test.go, Python in worker/tests/test_*.py
- Never hardcode secrets — use env vars from .env.example
- Error responses must use respondInternalError() — never leak details
- LLM calls go through LiteLLM (port 4000), never direct to Ollama
- Sandbox code must pass AST prefilter — no os, sys, subprocess, socket imports
- Skill templates in agent_skills table must NOT import os, sys, subprocess, or socket
- Redis accessed via go-redis/v9 client (api/ratelimit.go), never raw TCP
- DB connections via pooled_connection() or get_db_connection() (worker/database/pool_manager.py)
- Temporal activities use @activity.defn, workflows use @workflow.defn
- All LLM inputs wrapped with wrap_untrusted_data() for injection defense
- The adversarial review passes through on timeout — this is intentional, not a bug
- After modifying _legacy_activities.py, ALWAYS rebuild: docker compose build worker && docker compose up -d worker
- After modifying Go files, ALWAYS rebuild: docker compose build api && docker compose up -d api
- New activities go in worker/_legacy_activities.py + re-export in worker/activities/__init__.py
- New workflows go in worker/_legacy_workflows.py + re-export in worker/workflows/__init__.py
